Someone wrote:
> if you use the standard Cypher Block Chaining method of DES, and add one
> DES block worth of random data to the front.  The first block's "errors"
> will propagate through the rest of the data.

Steve Pope <spp@bob.eecs.berkeley.edu> wrote:
SP> does this mean that, to crack such a DES configuration by brute force,
SP> one would have to search a 120 bit key space --- 56 bit DES key, and 64
SP> bit initial state?  If that is true it would seem like a pretty strong
SP> mode of operation.

rudis+@cs.cmu.edu (Rujith S DeSilva) [that's me!] wrote:
RDS> When the 56-bit DES key is guessed, decrypting the first block will
RDS> give the 64-bit random initial block.

SP> If an initial block of random data is encrypted in this mode, and the
SP> resultant block of ciphertext is NOT TRANSMITTED, then my statement
SP> about needing to search a 120-bit key space would hold.

How would the bona fide recipient decrypt the message?

Later,
Rujith.

